Employee Insights¶

Using Data Science to Understand your Employees Better¶

Introduction¶

The average employee turn-over in technology is two years. With this, it's a miracle how any company gets anything done at all.

Maybe if more companies were better at retaining the employees they had, they wouldn't constantly be chanting WE ARE HIRING!

— DHH (@dhh) July 26, 2017

How happy and productive your employees has a direct co-relation with the success of your company. So why leave things to chance? Here's how we can use data science to help understand what makes your employees tick, so you can nip problems in the bud!

In this sample project, we'll use a dummy data-set that contains employee details and other demographics. We'll use data science techniques to get lots of insights, and finally try and see if we can predict whether an employee is likely to call it quits.¶

We'll use some of these Python libraries¶

  • numpy is a package in python that is used for scientific computing. It supports higher-order mathematical functions, higher dimensional arrays, matrices and other data structures.
  • pandas is a very popular library that is used for a lot of data analysis and statistics related problems.
  • time - standard module in python that allows for time related functions
  • display is a module in the IPython toolkit that helps you display data structures in a nice, readable format.
  • matplotlib is a very popular visualization library that lets you create a wide array of figures, charts and graphs in the IPython Notebook
  • seaborn is another visualization tool that uses matplotlib underneath, and provides you with easy-to-use APIs for visualization. It also makes your graphs more prettier!

The fields in the dataset include:

  1. Employee satisfaction level, scaling 0 to 1
  2. Last evaluation, scaling 0 to 1
  3. Number of projects
  4. Average monthly hours
  5. Time spent at the company in years
  6. Whether they have had a work accident
  7. Whether they have had a promotion in the last 5 years
  8. Sales (which actually means job function).
  9. Salarylow, medium or high
  10. Whether the employee has left. This will be our target label

Let's checkout the turnover percentage. As you can see, about 24% employees left and the rest 76% stayed¶

Insights¶

  • The mean satisfaction for employees who left is low.
  • The last evaluation score mean for both categorie of employee are very close. This sort-of tells us that there's a high chance of lot of highly evaluated employees leaving, or poorly evaluated employees are being retained.
  • The average working hours mean too is close to each other, this suggest that there's more to just than rigorous working hours for employee turnouts.
  • But the promotion mean is 4 times more for the employees who stayed. This also might mean that people who get promoted are less likely to leave the company and this could be a strategy to retain your best employees.

Feature selection¶

Firstly we need to identify the most important features for employee turnover. We'll be the some of the classifiers in the next section not for training purposes, but just for understanding which are the most important features that influence employee turnover. Here are the techniques we'll be using for feature selection -

  • Co-relation heatmap
  • Random Forest Classifier
  • XGBoost Classifier
  • Decision Trees (they reveal much more than that top features)

The heat-map earlier showed us that the average monthly hour feature is highly co-related to number of projects (obviously) and the evaluation. Due to this high co-relation this feature can be dropped while training with the classifiers in the next section.

Preparing the data for training¶

In [124]:
from sklearn.metrics import fbeta_score
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import numpy as np
plt.style.use('fivethirtyeight')
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (12,6)

df = data.drop(['last_evaluation_group','satisfaction_level_group'],axis=1)

# Convert these variables into categorical variables.
df["department"] = df["department"].astype('category').cat.codes
df["salary"] = df["salary"].astype('category').cat.codes

# Display the first 10 records
display(df.head(n=10))

# Create train and test splits
target_name = 'left'
X = df.drop('left', axis=1)

# obtain the target value. Its the employee turnover.
y = df[target_name]
# Split the data into test and training set.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.15, random_state=123, stratify=y)

Random Forest Classifier for feature selection¶

In [125]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV, cross_val_score, learning_curve

RFC = RandomForestClassifier()

RFC.fit(X_train,y_train)

rfc_predictions_train = RFC.predict(X_train)
rfc_predictions_test = RFC.predict(X_test)

rfc_training_accuracy_score = accuracy_score(y_train, rfc_predictions_train)
rfc_test_accuracy_score = accuracy_score(y_test, rfc_predictions_test)
print("Random Forest accuracy on training set:",rfc_training_accuracy_score)
print("Random Forest accuracy on testing set:",rfc_test_accuracy_score)

rfc_training_fbeta_score = fbeta_score(y_train, rfc_predictions_train, beta=0.5, average='micro')
rfc_test_fbeta_score = fbeta_score(y_test, rfc_predictions_test, beta=0.5, average='micro')
print("Random Forest fbeta score on training set:",rfc_training_fbeta_score)
print("Random Forest fbeta score on testing set:",rfc_test_fbeta_score)

#from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3)
dtree = dtree.fit(X_train,y_train)

## plot the importances ##
importances = dtree.feature_importances_
feat_names = df.drop(['left'],axis=1).columns


indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.title("Feature importances by DecisionTreeClassifier")
plt.bar(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color='lightblue',  align="center")
plt.step(range(len(indices)), np.cumsum(importances[indices]), where='mid', label='Cumulative')
plt.xticks(range(len(indices)), feat_names[indices], rotation='vertical',fontsize=14)
plt.xlim([-1, len(indices)])
plt.show()

We clearly see 3 red clusters in the visualization of satisfaction vs evaluation (see below). We can separate these clusters out using K-means clustering with 3 clusters and then analyze these groups. On analysis, we see some interesting patterns emerge -

  • Performing but unsatisfied: The left most red cluster corresponds to employees who performed well but were really unsatisfied and left the company. Why is this happening? The company is supposed to maintain the interests of well performing employees.
  • Not performing Not satisfied: The middle red cluster corresponds to employees who are not performing well and not happy too and they've left the company.
  • Performing and satisfied: Here is the most alarming cluster, the right-most red cluster on the top. These are well performing and satisfied employees who have left the company. It would very interesting to know why.

K-Means clustering¶

Let's use K-means clustering on the data of people who left the company. Since we saw a clear grouping in employees who left the company in the satisfaction vs evaluation scatter plot, let's use these features to separate out the clusters and perform further analysis on each one of them.

In [135]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# Obtain the data for the employees who've left the company.
data_left = df[df["left"]==1]

data_stayed = df[df["left"]==0]

print(data_left.shape)

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3,random_state=2)
kmeans.fit(data_left[["satisfaction_level","last_evaluation"]])

(3571, 10)

Performing Happy:  (977, 10)
Non-performing Unhappy:  (1650, 10)
Performing UnHappy:  (944, 10)

Insight:¶

It's disastrous to see that 977 of well performing and happy employees left and 944 of well performing employees who were unhappy left the company.

A Radar Chart on average features of employees who stayed and employees who left, from each of the three clusters, should help us find the most important factors for employee turnover.¶

# Code to draw Radar chart.
def _scale_data(data, ranges):
    (x1, x2) = ranges[0]
    d = data[0]
    return [(d - y1) / (y2 - y1) * (x2 - x1) + x1 for d, (y1, y2) in zip(data, ranges)]

  
class RadarChart():
    def __init__(self, fig, variables, ranges, n_ordinate_levels = 6):
        angles = np.arange(0, 360, 360./len(variables))

        axes = [fig.add_axes([0.1,0.1,0.8,0.8],polar = True, 
        label = "axes{}".format(i)) for i in range(len(variables))]
        _, text = axes[0].set_thetagrids(angles, labels = variables)
        
        for txt, angle in zip(text, angles):
            txt.set_rotation(angle - 90)
        
        for ax in axes[1:]:
            ax.patch.set_visible(False)
            ax.xaxis.set_visible(False)
            ax.grid("off")
        
        for i, ax in enumerate(axes):
            grid = np.linspace(*ranges[i],num = n_ordinate_levels)
            grid_label = [""]+["{:.1f}".format(x) for x in grid[1:]]
            ax.set_rgrids(grid, labels = grid_label, angle = angles[i])
            ax.set_ylim(*ranges[i])
        
        self.angle = np.deg2rad(np.r_[angles, angles[0]])
        self.ranges = ranges
        self.ax = axes[0]

    def plot(self, data, *args, **kw):
        sdata = _scale_data(data, self.ranges)
        self.ax.plot(self.angle, np.r_[sdata, sdata[0]], *args, **kw)

    def fill(self, data, *args, **kw):
        sdata = _scale_data(data, self.ranges)
        self.ax.fill(self.angle, np.r_[sdata, sdata[0]], *args, **kw)

    def legend(self, *args, **kw):
        self.ax.legend(*args, **kw)

Radar Graph interpretation¶

Insights:¶

  • The radar graph shows that the mean salary is the same for all cluster of employees. This clearly tells that the well performing employees need a raise.
  • It's clear why a large section of well performing employees are unsatisfied and they leave the company. The blue part in the radar graph indicates that these employees work way too many projects and thus spend far too many hours at office but still get paid the same like the others. Pretty soon they become unsatisfied. It's clear that they might under lot of stress at work and their load has to reduce to improve the chances of retaining them.
  • As you can see in the red, highly performing and satisfied employee who leave the company tend to spend more number of hours at office on few projects, and they also tend to stay longer in the company.

Now, can you predict an employee leaving the company in advance?¶

  • The second employee is reasonably satisfied with work, last evaluation was better than average, has neither too less nor too large number of projects or monthly hours, and has spent some decent time at the company. Such an employee is likely to stay, and our model predicts the same as well.
